## purpose
Defines the canonical architectural role of culture in CivilizationOS.

## design_intent
Culture is the bounded shared-pattern structure
through which norms,
customs,
styles,
symbolic forms,
and collective expression
become meaningful.

Culture is not identical to law or language.
It influences behavior and interpretation,
but must remain distinct from formal authority and from literal expression channels.

## architectural_position
Culture sits between:
- social participation
- nation/community identity
- language expression
- religion/education/history continuity
- art/custom/practice formation

## required_behavior
- cultural context must remain explicit
- shared-pattern basis must remain explicit
- current and historical cultural states must remain distinguishable
- culture must not masquerade as formal legal authority

## canonical_rules
- cultural norm does not automatically imply policy authority
- cultural projection must not erase source cultural context
- historical culture trace must remain queryable
- ambiguous cultural scope fails closed

## state_model
The culture domain distinguishes:
- declared culture context
- active culture context
- restricted culture context
- transformed culture context
- historical culture context

## actor_boundary
- participant/bearer
- operator
- reviewer
- adapter

## decision_matrix
- if cultural context is unclear, stop culture-sensitive interpretation
- if norm basis is unclear, fail closed
- if historical culture is referenced, preserve distinction
- if culture transforms, preserve prior trace

## review_checklist
- cultural context is explicit
- norm/pattern basis is explicit
- law/culture distinction is explicit
- historical distinction is explicit
